  "definition": "The global market for trading currencies in pairs (e.g., USD/EUR). It operates 24 hours a day on weekdays, offers the highest liquidity, and allows low starting capital. Often involves high leverage, and technical analysis is commonly used to navigate its complex economic drivers.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "The market operates 24 hours a day during the business week, closing only on weekends.",
    "It exhibits the highest global liquidity among all asset classes, ensuring easy trade execution.",
    "Trading requires very low starting capital, often with high leverage options available.",
    "It involves trading currency pairs, with price movements influenced by economic factors and news."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Forex is well-suited for day trading and scalping due to its 24/5 operation and deep liquidity. Traders can profit from frequent price fluctuations but must manage high leverage carefully. Technical analysis is effective for trading Forex without deep economic knowledge, though awareness of major economic events can help mitigate sudden volatility.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Over-leveraging due to low capital requirements, leading to rapid and large losses.",
    "Ignoring economic events entirely, assuming technical analysis alone makes Forex movements predictable."
  ],
